context: <a0_0><b5_0>St. Patrick's Street<b5_0/><a0_0/>, the main street of the city which was remodelled in the <a1_0>mid-2000s<a1_0/>, is known for the architecture of the buildings along its pedestrian-friendly route and is the main shopping thoroughfare. The reason for its curved shape is that <a2_0><b14_0>it originally was a channel of the River Lee that was built over on arches<b14_0/><a2_0/>. The General Post Office, with its limestone façade, is on Oliver Plunkett Street, on the site of <b6_0>the Theatre Royal<b6_0/> which was built in 1760 and burned down in <a3_0><b10_0>1840<b10_0/><a3_0/>. The English circus proprietor <b7_0><b11_0>Pablo Fanque<b11_0/><b7_0/> rebuilt an amphitheatre on the spot in 1850, which was subsequently transformed into <b12_0>a theatre<b12_0/> and then into <b13_0>the present <a4_0><b8_0>General Post Office<b13_0/><b8_0/><a4_0/> in 1877.  The Grand Parade is a tree-lined avenue, home to offices, shops and financial institutions. The old financial centre is the South Mall, with several banks whose interior derive from the 19th century, such as the <b9_0>Allied Irish Bank<b9_0/>'s which was once an exchange.
